## 1. identity-service — PostgreSQL, database `identity`

### 1.1 Schema

```sql
-- V1__create_identity_schema.sql
CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS citext;

CREATE TABLE roles (
    id    SMALLINT PRIMARY KEY,
    code  VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL UNIQUE            -- 'ADMIN' | 'CUSTOMER'
);

CREATE TABLE accounts (
    id             UUID PRIMARY KEY DEFAULT gen_random_uuid(),
    email          CITEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE,       -- ACC-002
    password_hash  TEXT NOT NULL,                -- ACC-001; hashing algorithm is app-layer, not a DB concern
    full_name      VARCHAR(200) NOT NULL,        -- ACC-001, ACC-011
    role_id        SMALLINT NOT NULL REFERENCES roles(id),
    status         VARCHAR(11) NOT NULL DEFAULT 'ACTIVE'
                       CHECK (status IN ('ACTIVE', 'DEACTIVATED')),   -- ACC-006
    created_at     TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),
    updated_at     TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()
);

CREATE INDEX idx_accounts_role_id ON accounts (role_id);
```

```sql
-- V2__seed_roles.sql   (filename fixed by ARCHITECTURE.md §9)
INSERT INTO roles (id, code) VALUES (1, 'ADMIN'), (2, 'CUSTOMER');
```

### 1.2 Design decisions

- **[Decision] Email uniqueness via `CITEXT`, not `LOWER(email)` + a functional index.** ACC-002 requires case-insensitive uniqueness while presumably still wanting to display the address as the user typed it. `citext` does both natively: comparisons and the unique index are case-insensitive, but the stored value keeps its original casing. A functional unique index on `LOWER(email)` would work too, but every query (not just the constraint) would then need to remember to lowercase the predicate — `citext` makes correct behavior the default instead of something every call site has to get right.
- **[Decision] `roles` as a lookup table, not a `VARCHAR`/enum column on `accounts`.** Only two values exist today (§2 of the business rules), so an inline check constraint would also work. A lookup table is still the better call here because `ARCHITECTURE.md` §9 already commits to seeding it via `V2__seed_roles.sql` as reference data — the design has to match that commitment — and it keeps `accounts` in 3NF (role name isn't repeated on every row).
- **`status` as a `CHECK`-constrained `VARCHAR`, not a lookup table.** Unlike roles, ACC-006 fixes this to exactly two values with no seed-data commitment anywhere in the architecture doc, and nothing suggests a status will ever need its own attributes. A second lookup table here would be a table for the sake of a table — a `CHECK` constraint gives the same integrity guarantee with less machinery.
- **Primary key is `UUID`, not `BIGSERIAL`.** `identity.proto`'s `GetUserRequest`/`UserResponse` already use `string user_id` — a `BIGSERIAL` would force a numeric↔string conversion at the gRPC boundary for no benefit. `gen_random_uuid()` is native to Postgres (13+), no extension required.
- **No email-verification or password-reset columns.** Explicitly out of scope (BUSINESS_RULES.md §8) — adding `verified_at` or `reset_token` columns now would be building for a feature that was deliberately excluded.

### 1.3 Indexing & performance

- `accounts.email` (unique, via `citext`) is the only index login needs — ACC-003/ACC-005 are both single-row lookups by email.
- `idx_accounts_role_id` supports an Administrator's "list all admins" / role-filtered support queries (ACC-011) without a sequential scan.
- No index on `status` — filtering by status is always combined with the email lookup on login (already covered) or is a full admin listing (small table, sequential scan is fine at this data volume); adding one now would be indexing for a query pattern nothing in the business rules asks for.

### 1.4 Data integrity

- ACC-002 (case-insensitive uniqueness) — `citext` unique constraint.
- ACC-006 (exactly one of two statuses) — `CHECK` constraint, not app-layer-only validation.
- ACC-010 (system must never have zero Administrators) is **not** enforceable as a static SQL constraint (it's a property of the *current row set*, not a single row) — this is deliberately left to the application/deployment process: exactly one Administrator account must exist before the system accepts its first request. **This document does not invent a seed email/password** — real login credentials are a deployment-time secret, not something to bake into version control. A `V3__seed_initial_admin.sql`-style migration is the right mechanism, but its actual values are an ops decision outside this document's scope.

### 1.5 Replication

- Runs on the shared Postgres 17 instance per `ARCHITECTURE.md` §9 (separate database, separate Flyway history table from `orders`).
- Production recommendation: primary + at least one async streaming replica, standard Postgres HA.
- **[Decision] Auth-path reads must go to the primary, not a replica.** ACC-007 says a Deactivated account can't log in or place orders — if a replica lag window let a stale "ACTIVE" row be read just after an Administrator deactivated that account, the gate ACC-007 depends on would silently fail open. Replicas are fine for ACC-011 admin/support lookups, where a few hundred milliseconds of staleness has no security consequence, but not for the login path or for the `GetUser` call order-service makes to gate ORD-001.

