## 2. catalog-service — MongoDB, database `catalog`

### 2.1 Schema (collection `products`)

```js
db.createCollection("products", {
  validator: {
    $jsonSchema: {
      bsonType: "object",
      required: ["_id", "name", "description", "category", "unitPrice", "stockCount", "status", "createdAt", "updatedAt"],
      properties: {
        _id:         { bsonType: "string" },                       // UUID, matches proto's string product_id
        name:        { bsonType: "string", minLength: 1 },          // CAT-001, CAT-005 (not unique)
        description: { bsonType: "string" },                        // CAT-001
        category:    { bsonType: "string", minLength: 1 },          // CAT-004
        unitPrice:   { bsonType: "decimal", minimum: 0, exclusiveMinimum: true }, // CAT-002 — Decimal128, never double
        stockCount:  { bsonType: "int", minimum: 0 },                // CAT-003
        status:      { enum: ["ACTIVE", "DEACTIVATED"] },            // CAT-008
        createdAt:   { bsonType: "date" },
        updatedAt:   { bsonType: "date" }
      }
    }
  },
  validationLevel: "strict",
  validationAction: "error"
});

db.products.createIndex({ status: 1, category: 1 });                 // browse: active products by category (CAT-007/CAT-008)
db.products.createIndex(
  { name: "text", description: "text" },
  { weights: { name: 5, description: 1 } }                            // search performance
);
```

### 2.2 Design decisions

- **[Decision] `category` is a plain indexed string field, not a separate `categories` collection.** CAT-004 only requires that a product belong to exactly one category — nothing in the business rules describes categories having their own attributes, an admin-managed lifecycle, or being read independently of a product. A reference collection would be solving a problem the business rules don't have. If category management becomes its own bounded concept later, that's new scope (mirrors how `BUSINESS_RULES.md` §8 treats out-of-scope items), not something to speculatively build now.
- **`$jsonSchema` validator instead of relying on app-layer validation alone.** MongoDB has no `CHECK` constraint, but a collection validator is the direct equivalent — `unitPrice > 0` (CAT-002) and `stockCount >= 0` (CAT-003) are enforced at the database, not just in Kotlin code that a future migration script or manual `db.products.updateMany` could bypass.
- **`unitPrice` is `Decimal128`, never a JS/BSON `double`.** Doubles cannot represent currency exactly (binary floating point); `Decimal128` is MongoDB's fixed-point type and is the only correct choice for money, matching `NUMERIC` on the Postgres side.
- **No `deletedAt` / hard-delete path.** CAT-009 forbids deleting a product that's ever been ordered, and GEN-003 says all records are retained indefinitely — the schema has no delete mechanism at all, only the `status` field. A product that's genuinely never been ordered can be removed with a plain document delete; that's an app-layer authorization decision (has it ever appeared in an `order_items` row?), not a schema concern.
- **No optimistic-concurrency/version field.** Handled instead by the atomic update in §2.3 — see there for why a version field would be redundant, not just omitted for simplicity.

### 2.3 Concurrency & data integrity (GEN-001)

Stock changes are single-document atomic updates, which is what actually makes the "last unit" race in GEN-001 correct without a multi-document transaction or an app-level lock:

```js
// ReserveStock
db.products.findOneAndUpdate(
  { _id: productId, status: "ACTIVE", stockCount: { $gte: quantity } },
  { $inc: { stockCount: -quantity }, $set: { updatedAt: new Date() } }
)
// null result => not found, deactivated, or insufficient stock; catalog-service reports failure (ORD-007), no partial effect.
```

```js
// ReleaseStock (ORD-012, on cancellation)
db.products.findOneAndUpdate(
  { _id: productId },
  { $inc: { stockCount: quantity }, $set: { updatedAt: new Date() } }
)
```

**[Decision] `ReleaseStock` is deliberately *not* conditioned on `status: "ACTIVE"`.** If a product is deactivated after an order containing it was placed, cancelling that order must still restore the correct stock count (ORD-012 doesn't carve out an exception for deactivated products) — conditioning the release on active status would silently under-count stock on a product that could later be reactivated.

### 2.4 Search & browse performance

- `{status:1, category:1}` compound index covers the two things every browse/search query filters on: CAT-008 (deactivated products are fully hidden) and category filtering.
- Text index on `name`/`description` covers product search (CAT-001 fields), weighted toward name matches.
- No index for a default sort order (e.g. price ascending) — the business rules don't specify one ("search relevance/ranking beyond basic browsing" is explicitly out of scope, §8), so none is added speculatively.

### 2.5 Replication

- Must run as a proper MongoDB replica set (1 primary + 2 secondaries minimum) in any environment beyond the single dev container in `docker-compose.yml` — required for automatic failover.
- **[Decision] `ReserveStock`/`ReleaseStock` and any stock-authoritative read must use read preference `primary`.** CAT-011 makes catalog-service the sole authority on stock — a stale secondary read during checkout could show stock as available when it's actually exhausted. Pure browse/list reads can use `secondaryPreferred` for load distribution; a few hundred milliseconds of staleness there is a UX nicety issue, not a CAT-011 violation, since the actual reservation is always re-checked atomically against the primary regardless of what the browse UI showed.

