## 5. Cross-service data duplication register

This is the explicit "check the business first, defend the decision" ledger the task asked for. Every row is a place data crosses a service boundary; everything *not* listed here was considered and rejected.

| Duplicated field | Lives in | Source of truth | Business rule requiring it | Why nothing more is duplicated |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `product_name_snapshot`, `unit_price_snapshot` | `order_items` (order-service) | catalog-service, at order time only | ORD-005, verbatim | No other catalog field (category, description, stock) is copied — no rule ever reads them from an order. |
| `product_id` | `order_items` | catalog-service | ORD-003 (a line item names one product) | Reference only, not a live join across DBs (forbidden by database-per-service) — a UI needing current catalog data for a product on an old order makes a fresh gRPC `GetProduct` call at read time. |
| `customer_id` | `orders` | identity-service | ORD-001, ORD-014 | ORD-014 only requires the *reference* to an order's buyer never change — it does not require freezing the customer's name/email onto the order. No profile field is duplicated; a UI showing "placed by Jane Doe" does a `GetUser` call at read time, same reasoning as above. |
| `accountId` | `notifications` | identity-service | NTF-003 | Reference only, same reasoning as `customer_id` above. |
| `orderId` | `notifications` | order-service | NTF-001, NTF-002 | Only the reference is stored — no order total or status is duplicated onto the notification. NTF-001–005 never describe a notification needing to display an amount, only that a "placed"/"cancelled" event occurred. |
| `message` | `notifications` | derived once, at write time, from `type` | NTF-004 (in-system record only) | This is generated text (e.g. "Your order has been placed"), not a synced copy of any other service's mutable field — it never needs to be re-fetched or kept in sync with anything, so it isn't really "duplication" in the coupling sense the task is asking about. |

No account email/name, no product category/description, and no order total are ever copied into another service's database. Every cross-service read that needs current data (not historical, order-time-of-record data) goes through the gRPC contracts already defined in `proto/identity-proto` and `proto/catalog-proto` — that boundary is what keeps these four databases actually decoupled rather than "coupled with extra steps."

